ons, and its potential to enhance democratic governance.Drawing on the latest work from economics, political science, and law, Inman and Rubinfeld assess different models of federalism and their relative abilities to promote economic efficiency, encourage the participation of citizens, and protect individual liberties. Under the right conditions, the authors argue, a federal democracy-including a national legislature with locally elected representatives-can best achieve these goals. Because a stable union between the national and local governments is key, Inman and Rubinfeld also propose an innovative method for evaluating new federal laws and their possible impact on state and local governments. Finally, to show what the adoption of federalism can mean for citizens, the authors discuss the evolution of governance in the European Union and South Africa's transition from apartheid to a multiracial democracy.Interdisciplinary in approach, Democratic Federalism brims with applicable policy ideas and comparative case studies of global significance. This book is indispensable for understanding the importance of federal forms of government-both in recent history and, crucially, for future democracies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCentral-local government relations. 0aFederal government. 0aIntergovernmental fiscal relations. 0aIntergovernmental tax relations. 0aRevenue sharing. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Economics / General.2bisacsh  aFIST.  aFederalism Impact Statement.  aadvantages and disadvantages of federalism.  aconstitutional law.  aconstitutional structure.  acontemporary federalism.  acooperative federalism.  ademocratic participation.  aeconomic development.  aeconomic efficiency.  aeconomic federalism.  aeconomics of federalism.  aemerging democracies.  afederal union.  afed